<subSubSection pageId="24" pageNumber="91" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="24.[227,348,1356,1382]" box="[227,348,1356,1382]" pageId="24" pageNumber="91">
<heading bold="true" box="[227,348,1356,1382]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="24" pageNumber="91" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[227,348,1356,1382]" pageId="24" pageNumber="91">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[227,1437,1402,1568]" pageId="24" pageNumber="91">
Species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ryckholt" authorityYear="1852" box="[363,513,1402,1428]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Vestinautilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="24" pageNumber="91" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[363,513,1402,1428]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="91">Vestinautilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with strongly depressed, rounded-trapezoidal whorl profile (ww/wh ~ 2.10), venter up to 
<quantity box="[388,475,1437,1463]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="24" pageNumber="91" unit="mm" value="30.0">30 mm</quantity>
conch diameter broadly arched with two shallow submarginal grooves, which disappear in the adult stage. Ventrolateral shoulder defined by a subangular margin; one sharp ridge is located on the umbilical wall near the ventrolateral shoulder. Whorls weakly embracing, coiling very high (WER ~2.55). Ornament with delicate growth lines.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[227,1293,1606,1678]" pageId="24" pageNumber="91" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="24.[227,362,1606,1632]" box="[227,362,1606,1632]" pageId="24" pageNumber="91">
<heading bold="true" box="[227,362,1606,1632]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="24" pageNumber="91" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[227,362,1606,1632]" pageId="24" pageNumber="91">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[227,1293,1652,1678]" box="[227,1293,1652,1678]" pageId="24" pageNumber="91">
From the Latin ‘ 
<emphasis box="[420,487,1653,1678]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="91">crista</emphasis>
’, meaning ‘crest’ and referring to the two lateral longitudinal ridges.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
