<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="92" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="25.[227,372,524,550]" box="[227,372,524,550]" pageId="25" pageNumber="92">
<heading bold="true" box="[227,372,524,550]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="25" pageNumber="92" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[227,372,524,550]" pageId="25" pageNumber="92">Description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[226,1437,573,897]" pageId="25" pageNumber="92">
<typeStatus box="[227,336,573,599]" pageId="25" pageNumber="92">Holotype</typeStatus>
MB.C.30473 is a desert-polished specimen with a diameter of 
<quantity box="[1107,1196,573,599]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.8" pageId="25" pageNumber="92" unit="mm" value="38.0">38 mm</quantity>
, showing the conch shape and small areas of ornament (
<figureCitation box="[643,730,610,636]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="25.[227,270,1999,2025]" captionTargetBox="[281,1386,1515,1950]" captionTargetId="figure-338@25.[269,1394,1504,1958]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="Fig. 20. Vestinautilus bicristatus sp. nov., holotype MB.C.30473 (Wendt &amp; Kaufmann Coll.) from Oued Temertasset. Scale bar units = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6885246" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6885246/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="92">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
). The conch is broadly cylindrical and subevolute (ww/dm = 0.84; uw/dm =0.37) with a very high coiling rate (WER =2.57). The whorl profile is strongly depressed (ww/wh =2.13) and shows a flattened venter, which possesses two submarginal external grooves at size stages between 17 and 
<quantity box="[503,587,722,749]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" pageId="25" pageNumber="92" unit="mm" value="35.0">35 mm</quantity>
diameter. These weaken considerably thereafter and are only visible as shallow longitudinal depressions at the maximum diameter of the specimen. The ventrolateral shoulder is distinguished by three edges, of which the two inner ones are strengthened by longitudinal ridges. Only small areas of shell ornament are visible; these show very fine growth lines on the venter with a deep external sinus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[224,1437,939,1152]" pageId="25" pageNumber="92">
Three 
<typeStatus box="[302,414,939,965]" pageId="25" pageNumber="92">paratypes</typeStatus>
in fragmentary preservation are available. They are larger specimens with whorl widths between 49 and 
<quantity box="[410,494,976,1003]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="25" pageNumber="92" unit="mm" value="80.0">80 mm</quantity>
, thus belonged to conchs with 
<quantity box="[841,983,976,1003]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" metricValueMax="9.0" metricValueMin="6.0" pageId="25" pageNumber="92" unit="mm" value="75.0" valueMax="90.0" valueMin="60.0">60 to 90 mm</quantity>
diameter. Two of them (MB.C.30474.2 and MB.C.30474.3; 
<figureCitation box="[467,606,1013,1040]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="26.[227,270,1963,1989]" captionTargetBox="[232,1430,552,1899]" captionTargetId="figure-117@26.[227,1437,550,1911]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="Fig. 21. Vestinautilus bicristatus sp. nov. from Oued Temertasset (all Korn et al. 2002 Coll.). A. Paratype MB.C.30474.1. B. Paratype MB.C.30474.2. C. Paratype MB.C.30474.3. Scale bar units =1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6885248" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6885248/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="92">Fig. 21B–C</figureCitation>
) show the imprint of the preceding whorl with sublateral longitudinal grooves in the dorsal region; in 
<typeStatus box="[600,701,1051,1077]" pageId="25" pageNumber="92">paratype</typeStatus>
MB.C.30474.3 the edges of the ventrolateral shoulder are also still visible. Both have a broadly rounded venter. The largest 
<typeStatus box="[946,1047,1089,1115]" pageId="25" pageNumber="92">paratype</typeStatus>
MB.C.30474.1 shows a shallow, broad depression in the middle of the venter at its largest diameter (
<figureCitation box="[1019,1128,1125,1152]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="26.[227,270,1963,1989]" captionTargetBox="[232,1430,552,1899]" captionTargetId="figure-117@26.[227,1437,550,1911]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="Fig. 21. Vestinautilus bicristatus sp. nov. from Oued Temertasset (all Korn et al. 2002 Coll.). A. Paratype MB.C.30474.1. B. Paratype MB.C.30474.2. C. Paratype MB.C.30474.3. Scale bar units =1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6885248" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6885248/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="92">Fig. 21A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[227,1436,1193,1294]" pageId="25" pageNumber="92">
<typeStatus box="[227,330,1194,1220]" pageId="25" pageNumber="92">Paratype</typeStatus>
MB.C.30474.3 shows the suture line with a broad and shallow external lobe and a narrow and shallow lateral lobe, which has a position on the umbilical wall (
<figureCitation box="[982,1090,1230,1257]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="26.[227,270,1963,1989]" captionTargetBox="[232,1430,552,1899]" captionTargetId="figure-117@26.[227,1437,550,1911]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="Fig. 21. Vestinautilus bicristatus sp. nov. from Oued Temertasset (all Korn et al. 2002 Coll.). A. Paratype MB.C.30474.1. B. Paratype MB.C.30474.2. C. Paratype MB.C.30474.3. Scale bar units =1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6885248" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6885248/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="92">Fig. 21C</figureCitation>
). The siphuncle has a slightly subcentral position towards the venter.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="26" lastPageNumber="93" pageId="25" pageNumber="92" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="25.[227,341,1336,1362]" box="[227,341,1336,1362]" pageId="25" pageNumber="92">
<heading bold="true" box="[227,341,1336,1362]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="25" pageNumber="92" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[227,341,1336,1362]" pageId="25" pageNumber="92">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[227,1436,1384,1448]" pageId="25" pageNumber="92">
<taxonomicName authority="Korn &amp; Bockwinkel, 2022" authorityName="Korn &amp; Bockwinkel" authorityYear="2022" box="[227,511,1384,1410]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Vestinautilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="25" pageNumber="92" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="bicristatus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[227,511,1384,1410]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="92">Vestinautilus bicristatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[520,613,1385,1411]" pageId="25" pageNumber="92" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
belongs to the species of the genus that possess a very broad whorl profile (ww/wh&gt; 2.00) and an ornament with only a few spiral ridges. In this respect, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sowerby" authorityYear="1825" box="[1269,1429,1421,1447]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Nautilidae" genus="Nautilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="25" pageNumber="92" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="cariniferus">
<emphasis box="[1269,1429,1421,1447]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="92">V. cariniferus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
,
</paragraph>
<caption pageId="25" pageNumber="92" startId="25.[227,270,1999,2025]" targetBox="[281,1386,1515,1950]" targetPageId="25">
<paragraph blockId="25.[226,1437,1999,2061]" pageId="25" pageNumber="92">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[227,318,1999,2025]" pageId="25" pageNumber="92">Fig. 20.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Korn &amp; Bockwinkel, 2022" authorityName="Korn &amp; Bockwinkel" authorityYear="2022" box="[324,605,1999,2025]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Vestinautilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="25" pageNumber="92" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="bicristatus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[324,605,1999,2025]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="92">Vestinautilus bicristatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[611,704,2000,2026]" pageId="25" pageNumber="92" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, holotype MB.C.30473 (Wendt &amp; Kaufmann Coll.) from Oued Temertasset. Scale bar units = 
<quantity box="[578,649,2035,2061]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="25" pageNumber="92" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="26.[225,1436,303,435]" pageId="26" pageNumber="93">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Foord" authorityYear="1891" box="[227,430,304,329]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Goniatitidae" genus="Coelonautilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ammonoidea" pageId="26" pageNumber="93" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="paucicarinatus">
<emphasis box="[227,430,304,329]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="93">V. paucicarinatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="de Koninck" authorityYear="1844" box="[443,557,304,329]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Nautilidae" genus="Nautilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="26" pageNumber="93" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="pinguis">
<emphasis box="[443,557,304,329]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="93">V. pinguis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Foord" authorityYear="1900" box="[610,785,303,329]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Vestinautilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="26" pageNumber="93" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="semiplicatus">
<emphasis box="[610,785,303,329]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="93">V. semiplicatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are similar, but these four species have a concave venter at least at times in ontogeny (
<bibRefCitation author="Sowerby J. D. C." box="[583,760,338,365]" pageId="26" pageNumber="93" refId="ref18499" refString="Sowerby J. D. C. 1825. The Mineral Conchology of Great Britain; or Coloured Figures and Descriptions of those Remains of Testaceous Animals or Shells, which have been preserved at various Times and Depths in the Earth: Vol. 5. Richard Taylor, London." type="book" year="1825">Sowerby 1825</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="de Koninck L. G." box="[774,983,338,364]" pageId="26" pageNumber="93" refId="ref17367" refString="de Koninck L. G. 1844. Description des animaux fossiles qui se trouvent dans le terrain carbonifere de la Belgique. H. Dessain, Brussels." type="book" year="1844">de Koninck 1844</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Foord A. H." box="[997,1137,338,364]" pageId="26" pageNumber="93" refId="ref17610" refString="Foord A. H. 1891. Catalogue of the Fossil Cephalopoda in the British Museum, part II. Containing the Remainder of the Suborder Nautiloidea, Consisting of the Families Lituitidae, Trochoceratidae, and Nautilidae, with a Supplement. Order of the Trustees, London." type="book" year="1891">Foord 1891</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Foord A. H." box="[1151,1210,338,364]" pageId="26" pageNumber="93" pagination="49 - 126" refId="ref17660" refString="Foord A. H. 1900. Monograph on the Carboniferous Cephalopoda of Ireland. Part III. Containing the Families Tainoceratidae, Trigonoceratidae, Triboloceratidae, Rineceratidae, Coloceratidae, and Solenocheilidae (in Part). Monographs of the Palaeontographical Society 54: 49 - 126. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 02693445.1900.12035492" type="journal article" year="1900">1900</bibRefCitation>
). The most similar 
<taxonomicName authority="Korn &amp; Bockwinkel, 2022" authorityName="Korn &amp; Bockwinkel" authorityYear="2022" box="[229,379,373,399]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Vestinautilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="26" pageNumber="93" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="bicristatus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[229,379,373,399]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="93">V. bicristatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[385,475,374,400]" pageId="26" pageNumber="93" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is the species 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Korn, Miao &amp; Bockwinkel" authorityYear="2022" box="[640,738,373,399]" class="Cephalopoda" family="Trigonoceratidae" genus="Vestinautilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nautilida" pageId="26" pageNumber="93" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="padus">
<emphasis box="[640,738,373,399]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="93">V. padus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which shows the same conch dimensions, but differs in the lack of the submarginal ventral grooves (
<bibRefCitation author="Korn D. &amp; Miao L. &amp; Bockwinkel J." box="[707,902,408,434]" pageId="26" pageNumber="93" pagination="104 - 129" refId="ref18166" refString="Korn D., Miao L. &amp; Bockwinkel J. 2022. The nautiloids from the Dalle a Merocanites of Timimoun (Tournaisian - Visean boundary, Algeria). European Journal of Taxonomy 789: 104 - 129. https: // doi. org / 10.5852 / ejt. 2022.789.1635" type="journal article" year="2022">
Korn 
<emphasis box="[776,835,408,434]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="93">et al.</emphasis>
2022
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
